The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But it is not entirely clear to physicists that this is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely safe.
In any case, we assume that this is Higgs, as the chances of making a mistake seem small. We will see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because it will end up getting hurt.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli's exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And on the other side are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Particle Adventure website that, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I should point out here, are not the exotic animals we could believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disorders” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a bit as if it were an ice pond in which only a thick rock could slide over the surface.
That’s why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN’s (the big hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand by itself stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (such as the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what can all these investigations "contribute" to?, asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to screen for differences between observations and predictions of MS.
On the other hand, many fervently wish to be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation relating to gravity (ups!) or to dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day lives are hard to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say it won’t have any.
For you to see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would provoke.
They interfered with scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light sensor in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not his original intention at all, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that we never know...
