As lawmakers and human rights defenders discuss the consequences of the mandatory review law, scammers who trade in “false” certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force, according to which every labor immigrant must take an examination to check his knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service provision sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to pass the examination of the language, if not also that of Russian history and the fundamentals of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
The exception is citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who managed to obtain their certificates of education and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 shall not be subject to this law.
Usefulness, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centers will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the People’s Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the test in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 centers of this type are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the exam was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law came into force, often managed to ask the press this question: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the mandatory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First of all, the representatives of the Immigration Service answer, this will reduce the number of people suffering "labor slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labor migrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Immigration Service of Russia in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before you leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are faced by immigrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without an understanding of the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, take a “paid trip” to a creepy, narrow cove, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have received countless complaints from our immigrants.
“In their homeland they are promised one thing, but when they arrive they are cheated, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages,” says Tolib Sharipov, head of the labour immigration department of the Tajikistan Immigration Service.
Don't be angry, Chief!
However, meanwhile, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families don’t even have anything to feed the children, let alone dress them up, put on their shoes and buy them what they need for school.
Upon reaching adolescence, these guys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if you do not know the language, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as the language law is concerned, rights defenders point out an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and in the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred rubles.
The employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"We are asked for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajikistan citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be a prick, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several “false” certificates of language proficiency have already been seized by Federal Immigration Service officials.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time longer to study the basic course of the language.
In addition, non-Russian-speaking immigrants will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
