In recent days, a wave of protests has begun in the United States against low wages paid in Walmart supermarkets and restaurants of popular fast food chains, such as "McDonald's", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken".
For now no one dares to say whether or not this wave will reach the nine points, or whether it is destined to lose strength and settle down in its early stages.
The protest actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to the modest wage increases perceived by Walmart workers and those of the fast food system, the goal of protest organizers is the creation of workers’ unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has hardly been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
The actions began last week, after Thanksgiving Day, the so-called "Black Friday". That day, in the United States began the orgy of sales that captured millions of inhabitants, and that was sometimes accompanied by clashes.
That day, some workers at Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs and formed protest pickets alongside unions and left-wing activists at Walmart stores, whose products target modest and moderate-income people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in their stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those in larger supermarkets.
That’s why many poorly paid Walmart workers buy only at work.
Availability and product assortment have made Walmart one of the largest corporations in America.
According to two critics, Walmart can afford to sell products at very low prices, in part because it pays its workers little.
The latter also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or hand scanners.
That “Black Friday” rally participants demanded the increase in wages and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation went from $30 to $100 a month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who gets $9.5 an hour, this expense is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average salary to $12 an hour, it will cost the corporation $3.2 trillion.
This is about 1.1% more than you spend on wages now.
If Walmart puts the pay rise on consumers’ shoulders, every visit to the store will cost them just 46 cents more.
In a year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they spend now.
Walmart supporters say the protest took place in only nine states and did not cause any loss to the corporation.
Black Friday extended in its stores from 8 p.m. on Thursday to midnight the next day and, during that time, Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, its cash registers made nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company’s representative, Dan Fogelman, said in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post website that they left their job “less than five” Walmart employees and that the protest had been nothing more than “another PR stunt,” organized by the workers’ union.
"Free box!"
The protests continued this week in New York, in which the targets were not precisely Walmart department stores (which in this progressive city do not appreciate them, and for now there are none), but "McDonald's" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and then they don't even give you sick leave and they don't pay you for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, according to federal and New York law, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast-food restaurants are increasing it over time, but only slightly, and on average, ordinary workers receive $8.90 an hour in New York.
No one earns less than them in this city.
How it is possible to survive in New York with that money, for me it is something incomprehensible.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers would walk past McDonald’s and work there, behind the counters, part-time after school, even though they still lived with their parents.
Few saw this as the main source of income or planned to stay there for a long time.
Now, I constantly stumble upon some interviews with McDonald’s workers who complain that they have to live on this salary, and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, in a forum of the Wall Street Journal there is a comment whose author points out that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know what to give them to eat.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday at McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that fast food cashiers and cooks start paying at least $15 an hour, i.e., double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that workers’ unions be set up in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from impeding this right and punishing trade union activists with cunning and dismissals.
On the other hand, administration rarely makes life easier for them.
