You are talking about the problems of our country with the transfer of legislation regulating the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized in a different way?
As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
Competences are also somewhat analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of account are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Accounts.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not clear exactly what is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I do not like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it were not so, it would be of no benefit to them to collaborate with our office, don't you think?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been stated in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post controls, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, we are looking at the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of the selection process are corrected and the like.
Do you consider the passage of this law to be beneficial or rather a stumbling block to the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal ruling, which has no bearing on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDGs would not bother employers with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system, referring to the fact of being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>varc system prohibited or allowed?
