The MVRDV architecture studio shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "book mountain" - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there’s finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: “Furthermore, the building is beautiful.”
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one likes to go into those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom town located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, boasts the dubious honor of having stood up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was that the politicians decided that there was only one way to improve the statistics: they had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the contest presentation in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, the so-called <0x60>Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain rises in its intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded with the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town with no history, which until now had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall after whose white facade one would rather sense a central dairy, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But most of all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the real lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant headlight unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up you can see the benches of the park, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally bookshelves are arranged along the facade and in the center there is a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to step up the classic spatial configuration and take the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well taken advantage of: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of black shelves that assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even the most day-to-day architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And so it is like one day, in a Frisian farm, we come across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of a few millimeters thick has been used as the basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this tissue was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to obtain plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Despite the fact that the mountain of books is located under a huge pyramid of glass, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden circles located transversely to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic shutters.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Also, Chinese traditional medicine professor Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She qualifies the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; currently it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
