Szabo: "The Germans must play a more protagonist role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather grim diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories the status of observer state of the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also refrained from establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because he is currently reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not used to doing so.
I think they are still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they have already started the path towards a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn’t give it that much importance since it’s not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the Palestine vote?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys a huge degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps with this, Germany has managed to earn some respect.
After all, all this has only demonstrated that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, there are different views on the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the U.S. has clearly shown itself in favor of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration is secretly showing a great deal of understanding toward the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I believe that the true disparity of opinion does not really have the magnitude attributed to it.
If we look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must push things from their own position.
That is exactly what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship it maintains with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as an important international actor? Does Germany really want to take on a leading role?
Or do you still find it difficult to accept that leadership?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is always somewhat uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country continues to struggle to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as a major player, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Seen in this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should show a receptive attitude towards the different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The U.S. influence in European politics is diminishing more and more, but the EU is not covering that gap at the moment, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take on a more prominent role.
Even if they don’t like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular town, c’est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a globally known brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the real eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be justified.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer for Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he holds seats of the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the brand name Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are large warehouses of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different nature: on behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have “fished” a rich man.
Chinese authorities don’t feel guilty.
“It’s detrimental to the business, we have to fight it,” Pattloch demands.
“The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage to the image is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are in the millions, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The process can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had been so long that the name subject of the lawsuit had already become a “market reality.”
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged his brand in China,” Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo’s buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that largely reminded BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the work emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is usual in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This would be a new record and means that China is leading the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, which amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed for rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg demonstrates.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich appeal.
In the following two instances Freudenberg has been right, but the opposite party is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
The case has now reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where a decision is still pending.
Wentzler is confident that he can resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate the internal costs; the business file has had to review files up to a hundred years old to be able to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposite party a “six-figure sum in euros” with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
in particular if the imitators are guaranteed rights there on unprotected trade marks.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
Long ago the group abandoned this commercial sphere, however managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend that German companies be extremely prudent when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what needs to be done is to "register also in China everything that may be susceptible to protection", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic may be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license rights by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: Dancing, Singing, Helping
Imbongi choir rehearsed in Heidelberg and AIDS orphans cheered in Swaziland
The story of a bond capable of exceeding much more than 8,733 kilometers away.
