To foster cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two to three years through South Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, fighting spirit, hope and confidence in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost end of the African continent still remember from the apartheid era.
A bus full of whites singing songs in a language of blacks; so much recognition not only brings with it an excellent atmosphere and a lot of joy, but has also managed to tear off a couple of tears from some other angry border soldier.
The trip always takes them to Esitjeni, where the singers visit the sponsored children.
Although this small population barely appears on the maps, in the valley of the Ezulweni River it is well known.
“Close to Esitjeni, there the light shines,” the locals say.
And after traveling the 8,733 kilometres straight back to Heidelberg to the rehearsal rooms on Bergheimer Street full of singers marking the passage, one realizes that it is also possible to see its light shining from there.
