Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was held in maximum-security detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked questions to Manning and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the locksmiths as "excellent" and the treatment received on the premises in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers who visited him had told him about those issues and indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the registry.
"They were writing 'no incident' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he received during the January 2011 meeting with a board tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed on a form months earlier.
