Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21, this week’s clashes have reinforced the hawks on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has received a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on Gaza’s 1.7 million people in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to end Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its ruthless rivals of Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that time plays in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been the closest Muslim ally to Israel, has embraced the Hamas cause, as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s richest and most dynamic states.
Exhilarating Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hezbollah militia party dominates, through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
Instead, the Muslim Brotherhood are Hamas’s cousins and its leaders depend more on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
In the meantime, Israel’s hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep quieter... for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States is stronger than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel has prospered, especially under Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, in part thanks to the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of a territory aspiring to become a state of Palestine, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to increase despite the illegality of international legislation.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even tougher-line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, is in a good position.
Why pamper those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets like their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their head.
The hard wing may be imposed, although the Arab spring could alter its calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the area’s superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to bring about a ceasefire is a good hope and could mark the beginning of something.
The Israelis, too, should think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a dustbin that will one day explode in the territories occupied by Israel, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and the demographics are worsening as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to reject Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution remains that preached by sensible people on both sides, the majority of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and the cession of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more impetus to the outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must start curbing the entry of weapons into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with exchanges of land and a shared Jerusalem.
Non-Arabs should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual state category at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he failed to present his own plan for peace.
Again in the White House, he seems equally reticent to devote his attention to her.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The General Tobacco Packaging Act comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases shine on boxes of a green off, which are the same for all brands of tobacco
Australian tobacco and generic packaging law, a pioneer in the world, comes into force and replacing the logos and colors of the brands with a wrapper of an olive green shutdown, horrific images of body parts with diseases and representations of sick children and babies for being children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed in a small font type.
It is the strictest regime in the world applied to tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia says the goal is to deter young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit glamorous.
It relies on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never do so.
“It can be seen that children, even from a very early age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest rates of smokers in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies said the law would encourage the black tobacco market, in which cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
“The legislation will have serious unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia.
Others say their business has benefited from the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha, of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, said the demand for silicone pipettes and covers to cover the unpleasant images of the boxes had skyrocketed almost from scratch two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a rejection of the law in the Supreme Court.
Ms. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and that she was expecting more stocks.
"For us it's a good deal."
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector to which the plan is aimed.
After a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most sellers not to put cigarettes in sight, tobacco marketing has gone online.
Australia has banned internet advertising to local businesses and websites, but cannot restrict it to foreign pages.
“If you market tobacco and you only have this small window to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in reviews of brands from “walking citizens” published on social networking websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if it’s just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
The British American Tobacco of Australia indicated that the industry focuses more on what the new regulations imply than on marketing.
The industry has even come to pay for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to refuse the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being restricted unfairly, even though none of these countries has a significant volume of trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had held talks with other countries that are considering similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the requirement to include images in the boxes.
They are currently mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia, many smokers are challenging.
“The pictures don’t affect me.
I just don’t pay attention to them.”
“Take the cigarette and save the package,” says Victor El Hage as he buys a package with the image of a tumor in his mouth.
“Honestly, there’s only one reason I would quit smoking: for my daughter.”
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack pond in central Sydney, points out that uniform boxes make it more difficult for him to place them on the shelves.
“It usually took an hour to unwrap a delivery; now it takes four,” Yu says.
“The government should have totally banned tobacco and then, it’s, okay, it’s over and we shut down the store,” he says as he raises his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it’s not so bad to get a little bored
During the Thanksgiving holidays this year, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is pretty boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, like books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it’s okay that both we and our children get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we don’t experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in a good way?
Yes, sir.
And no.
But, we will talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press, says, it is not.
“In fact, the history of boredom is very long,” he says.
In the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin on boredom dating back to the 1st century AD.
We also need to think about how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in very different ways,” says John D. Eastwood, a psychology professor at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and putting the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you.”
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the process of attention, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boring can sound awfully similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that while they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be their own.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to an all-volume television show that kept no relation, others listened to it with the low volume, so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they found it difficult to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
“When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the distraction can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like spotting defective parts on a manufacturing line, music that distracts you can help you not get bored.”
“In fact, we currently know that moving or doing scribbles, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight it, as they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a “boring trend scale” in the 1980s.
The scale includes issues like “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do it all.”
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current percentages of boredom, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that “adolescents are a period in which boredom reaches its highest levels,” largely because both children and teens are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into the consumption of substances as a method of combating it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“Busty is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what’s most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to dose himself,” says Professor Fenske.
And “that ability to dose applies to other situations,” he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain themselves, but learns to control themselves better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“As we see it, we need to get bored more, but boredom is too distressing and unsettling a desire to relate it to something worthwhile,” he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.”
Colorado: No Book of Instructions for the New Marijuana Use Act
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old student at a community college and soccer player in southeastern Colorado, is facing criminal proceedings for something that will soon be legal across the state: possession of marijuana stones and a pipe he used to smoke it.
Orozco says that one day in September, he and some friends drove through Lamar, in the plains near the Kansas border, when they were stopped by police.
Police found marijuana in the car and some time later Orozco received a subpoena for possession of drugs and related items (minor offenses each involving a $100 fine) informing him of the date of the trial.
“They treat us like criminals,” Orozco says.
And they are?
In the weeks of uncertainty following Colorado’s vote to legalize possession of small amounts of recreational marijuana, the response in hundreds of minor drug possession cases depends less on the law than the location.
Hundreds of minor marijuana possession offenses are being overturned both here and in Washington State, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped filing charges against those over the age of 21 for small-scale possession, which will be legally approved once the law comes into force in the coming weeks.
But Colorado’s most conservative district prosecutors have pledged to move forward with open cases for marijuana possession and are still citing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains, are voting to prevent recently authorized marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“All this is changing so fast that I don’t know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, police chief at Aurora, just east of Denver.
Those in charge of regulation in Washington state are also turning the tables.
And they continue to seek advice to establish a system of production, manufacturing, distribution and sales licenses, all before the deadline of December 1, 2013.
They say that, for better or worse, Colorado is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana use, first for therapeutic purposes and now for recreational use.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide,” said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Control Commission.
But Mr. Smith admits that any place or system can only make suggestions about what might work.
“There is no real precedent that serves as a model for us,” he says.
Washington's I-502 law goes into effect on December 6, which also leaves a year during which you will swim between two waters, since the licensing system in that state will not yet exist, but possession will be legal.
In addition, there are some delicate mechanical issues that need to be resolved during that period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state’s requirement to provide “adequate access” to licensed marijuana and its prohibition to conduct cannabis business within a radius of less than 300 meters of schools, parks, children’s play areas or children’s centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” says Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently created research group.
On November 21, Oates, Aurora’s police chief, sent an email to his police officers informing them that the city’s prosecutor would stop bringing lawsuits for minor misdemeanors for possession of marijuana to people over the age of 21 and that police would stop bringing charges against those crimes “with immediate effect.”
Police chief Oates said they would be in charge of enforcing the city’s regulations governing the cultivation of marijuana for therapeutic purposes and that they would continue to pursue drug traffickers and sellers.
In Weld County, in northern Colorado, the district attorney, Ken Buck, represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to pursue cases of possession of marijuana, primarily to pressure consumers who decide to receive treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
“Our office has an obligation to bring legal action against those offenses that were criminal at the time they occurred,” Buck said in a statement.
The response has been complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana legalization initiative.
Grand Junction Police, the largest city in the county, no longer cite adults for possession of small amounts.
County District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending cases for possession.
"I don't think he's wasting his time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of voters supported the measure, it was never considered that bringing recreational marijuana use into the government and the judicial system was going to be easy.
The contradictory reactions that arise throughout the state show a marked ambivalence among officials regarding the great ecological experiment in this state.
“It’s a cultural barrier with the district’s prosecutors,” said Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents those accused of marijuana possession and who is a local spokesperson for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
“They’ve spent so much time taking people to court that, in fact, they can’t yet accept that it’s legal,” he said.
As the first states to consider small amounts of marijuana in the same way as if it were alcohol, Colorado and Washington are preparing to become national drug legalization test cases.
While lawyers and state officials have a new legal sales boundary, they also look forward to receiving directions from the federal government, which still envisions considering the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal offenses.
Advocates of the legalization of marijuana hope that the Department of Justice will give in.
Although there have been some outstanding arrests of patients and marijuana sellers for therapeutic purposes, the federal government has mostly allowed marijuana sales businesses for these purposes to exist in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
“While anti-drug agents are likely not to knock down doors to confiscate a small drug bag, they will likely be reluctant to allow state-regulated stores to operate for the sale of recreational marijuana, permitted under the new law,” said Kevin A. Sabet, a former anti-drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local governments approved moratoriums on any new marijuana store, even though it will be about a year before any of them can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose adopted a six-month ban and is likely to pass it next week.
“We don’t want to get into a situation where we authorize someone and then we have a serious problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
"Our community voted against this amendment.
We are studying in favor of what the community voted against voting in favor of what the state voted for."
There are many questions about this.
Petronella Wyatt: 'They harassed me until I was kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory'
You don’t attack college students for their views just now
I don’t remember a time in my life when I wasn’t dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a Greek symposium of the contemporary era that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thinking and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue the career of History, I had already made the suitcases, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started to cry.
My friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had left because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson announced jokingly that he had left me because I was being forced to drink in sloppy cups.
The truth was less fun.
I got out of there.
Yes, I did, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my flamboyant name, or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for a single reason, which in the cradle of the supposed illustration turned out to be something intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the conservative party.
You may be wondering what that comes to now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of right-wing students is suffering a similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred for the students of the conservative party is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them claimed the same level of equality of rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the JCR (Graduate Student Group) of Corpus Christi College claim that they are “often seriously sidelined, personally attacked and treated as non-gratuitous people” for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on their college’s equal opportunity committee to make sure they can express their views freely.
His situation was not favoured by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics and presenting the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Party Association of the University of Oxford (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with the silver handle.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated as “Turkish heads” by the introduction of higher enrolment rates.
Luke Black, 20-year-old and vice president of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing trend of leftists in universities.
People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, 19, who is elected president of the OUCA, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are centre-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the intellectual debate environment, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first weeks at Oxford I was more alone than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
The hatred for the Conservative Party was at its highest point.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an "honoris causa" title following cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have shocked any Stalinist.
Already during the first days of the welcome week to the new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that was waiting for me.
I found that not only did the professors turn a blind eye to the mockery of conservative university students, but they willingly participated in it.
The policy of the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s opposition to apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the seminary’s wooden halls.
The first I attended was to translate 18th-century French texts into English and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (already deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
Don't say a word.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
“Are the Thatcherists refusing to learn French, or are they simply fools?” he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning with the tears I was trying to contain.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” Pitt grumbled.
I went back to my room like a grieving soul.
That night I sat alone at dinnertime in college; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
“I’m afraid that’s how it goes.
They get involved with anyone who's suspected of being Tory.
It's very complicated for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be even worse for you.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be Labourists.”
Later, in a local pub, I tried to hide it.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Ms. Thatcher said.
That trick was useless.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted this song.
I became the dirty pervert.
“How do the Tories have sex?” one asked.
"They beat each other, don't they?"
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could he ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to stay with people who thought like me only after dark?
Would I have to become a laborer and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that were waiting for me presented themselves as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my college.
They hated him for being not only of the Conservative party, but also an adviser to Thatcher on foreign policy and one of the people who wrote his speeches to him.
I was barely there.
He hated the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and for its adherence to the Marxist-Determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he said.
I began to move daily from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, finding refuge in my more open metropolitan-minded family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But if it’s the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
“They would never do that, not there among my dear dream needles.
Even my communist friends have always had an impeccable attitude.”
His sore eyes began to cloud.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
My heart would break if you left it."
Tired of so many trips to London, my emotional stamina was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of History had insinuated, quite seriously, that I was an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed” me and called them “stupid old men.”
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my university career at Oxford.
At that time, my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch’s press.
My door was locked.
I was inside in fear, and after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you'll call me a weak cry.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only formed 14 Conservative Party prime ministers but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentine prefers elegance to notoriety"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentine: Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC speaks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer has recognized it during the inauguration of "Valentine: Master of Sewing", a retrospective apotheosis that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his "maison" over the past 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without its distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rare and distant world of nobility.
In the first room of this exhibition, open until March 3, there are plenty of private letters and photos with the signature of the most garnished of the aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, through Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England.
Valentino teaches these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from the humble fashionista of the city of Voghera, in northern Italy, to the idol of the international jet-set.
Being in love with royalty has nothing wrong.
“At least they don’t turn off their fangs on your magnificent carpet like some beautiful pop music celebrities do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular host and entertains with generosity and elegance.
