The Hardest Craft in the World: The Human Mules by Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano play life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the Earth’s bowels solidifies as it comes into contact with the air.
After tearing off large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, keeping the balance and carefully measuring its steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
They know that any skirmish could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who was laid off years ago by the risks of Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly loading the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the balance that a mining company has located a little further down, at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents euros) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As usual it is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually performs three doors a day.
It takes three hours each and ends up ground, but they allow you to add 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery to such inhuman effort, it is triple what I would win in the field.
“The miners’ newspaper is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the fee was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as strong as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing hide and seek at the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to bill him despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that the volcano releases.
It’s the price you have to pay to get your dream.
“I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist of a hotel, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two o’clock in the morning because sulfur does not stop manning at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its penguin benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs nor does it supply any equipment to porters, who work on their own and to both weight.
In fact, they don’t even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) camera surcharge that, next to the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance, the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is for the beasts and not for the people,” protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old gifted porter who has been at the Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working “as much as he can” because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, of their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and sores in the hips.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at his 53 years old.
Every day, he and his companions pull 15 tons of sulfur out of the volcano, which three trucks transfer to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat path between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the world’s toughest trades: the one made by the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore Seeks Babies to Save the Economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
“The population of Singapore needs to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, we fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem unlikely that these verses are part of a peppermint pill ad, but despite that — or perhaps because of that — the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references like “Let’s put a bao (bubble) in the oven” to laugh at Singapore’s birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, is hoping that with the announcement they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do “his national duty.”
This is something purely from the internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world to reproduce ourselves, so we felt this was a topic we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as throwing perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don’t we do the most creative thing we can to solve this problem, which is writing a rap?
1.2 children
The one that doesn’t take it so lightly is the government of Singapore.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriages and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech state city in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and their strict social controls.
Singapore’s birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 – known as the replacement rate – was in 1976.
So why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it’s due to a “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“That has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and forming a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the rise in singleness, and to delaying marriage and births, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to cope with the declining population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where barely disguised xenophobia abounds against many new immigrants, in particular the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The surge in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party last year experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with the highest quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs, and immigration policies, Singapore’s example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved on to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have surfaces of 46 square meters and have been very successful sales.
However, there is concern that they may promote a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family-friendly homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units run out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidelines for developers, who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too Stressed
Singapore is a state city.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the financial district of the center doesn’t seem like they’re going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so a lot of people are postponing it,” says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But for me it’s important to have my own money and time,” says another 20-year-old.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans are the ones who have the final say.
